\@writefile{toc}{\contentsline {subsubsection}{\numberline {2.2.1}Brain samples, RNA-seq}{4}}
\@writefile{lof}{\contentsline {figure}{\numberline {1}{\ignorespaces  Quantifying allelic bias of expression in human individuals using the read count ratio statistic \(S_{ig}\). The strength of bias towards the expression of the maternal (red) or paternal (blue) allele of a given gene \(g\) in individual \(i\) is gauged with the count of RNA-seq reads carrying the reference allele (small closed circles) and the count of reads carrying an alternative allele (open squares) at all SNPs for which the individual is heterozygous. The differences in the unobserved allelic bias between individual \(i_1\) and \(i_2\) arise only from biological differences such as their disease status (black and gray silhouettes), age, or gender. In addition to these, the differences in the observed read count ratio also reflect variation from technical sources like tissue preparation, or RNA sequencing. Note the sampling bias towards older individuals in institution \(A\) relative to \(B\). }}{5}}
\newlabel{fig:study-design}{{1}{5}}
